1) Install EAS CLI (once)
npm i -g eas-cli

2) Login to Expo (once)
eas login

3) Make sure your project has an Expo config

You should have app.json (or app.config.js).
(If you already do, skip.)

4) Install expo-updates
npx expo install expo-updates

5) Configure EAS Update (adds config to app.json)
npx eas update:configure

6) Create EAS project + build config
npx eas build:configure

7) Do your first build (required to enable updates)

Pick one:

Android

npx eas build --platform android


iOS

npx eas build --platform ios


Both

npx eas build --platform all

8) Publish updates later (no rebuild needed)
npx eas update --branch main --message "My update"

9) (Optional but recommended) Use a preview branch for testing
npx eas update --branch preview --message "Test update"

Quick notes

Steps 1–2 are one-time setup.

Step 7 (first build) is the key step that makes EAS Update work on installed apps.

If you tell me whether you’re building iOS, Android, or both, I’ll tailor the exact commands (and the right eas.json profiles) to your setup.